<subSubSection id="D4DAF09E03220920FF43B0A6CCE9CA59" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="9C7FA31503220920FF43B0A6C90BC917" blockId="6.[142,757,243,295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FF43B0A6C9B2C938" box="[142,499,243,265]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<typeStatus id="437B1DB703220920FF43B0A6C882C939" box="[142,195,244,265]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Type</typeStatus>
species here designated:
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FDCBB0A1C90BC917" authority="Parent, 1931: 20" authorityName="Parent" authorityPageNumber="20" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipalpus">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FDCBB0A1CAB4C938" box="[518,757,243,264]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Achalcus albipalpus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="F851DEE403220920FF43B140C90BC917" author="Parent O" box="[142,330,274,295]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" pagination="1 - 21" refId="ref24768" refString="Parent O. 1931. Dipteres Dolichopodides de l'Amerique du Sud. Especes nouvelles figurant dans la collection Schnuse conservees aux Staatliche Museen fur Tierkunde und Volkerkunde zu Dresden. Abhandlungen und Berichte aus den Staatliches Museen fur Tierkunde und Volkerkunde in Dresden 18: 1 - 21, 3 pl." type="journal article" year="1931">Parent, 1931: 20</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C7FA31503220920FF43B115CAB7C94B" blockId="6.[142,758,327,380]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FF43B115C893C96C" box="[142,210,327,348]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Head:</emphasis>
All postoculars dark. Arista at most about as long as first three antennal joints (exc. 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FD82B134CAA6C94B" baseAuthorityName="Van Duzee" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[591,743,358,379]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Enlinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsae">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FD82B134CAA6C94B" box="[591,743,358,379]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. edwardsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C7FA31503220920FF43B1C9CBA7C965" blockId="6.[142,758,411,617]" lastBlockId="6.[806,1422,196,341]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FF43B1C9C9C2C980" box="[142,387,411,432]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Thorax and abdomen</emphasis>
: Six DC. Small additional setae between posthumeral, presutural and first two DC bristles present in some species. Mostly six pubescent abdominal segments (five in 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FDD6B1A5CAF3CA3C" authorityName="Parent" authorityYear="1931" box="[539,690,503,524]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipalpus">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FDD6B1A5CAF3CA3C" box="[539,690,503,524]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. albipalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FF43B244C96BCA1A" box="[142,298,533,555]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevinervis">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FF43B244C96BCA1A" box="[142,298,533,555]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. brevinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Hypopygium (
<figureCitation id="04FBBF9003220920FE32B247CA14CA1A" box="[511,597,533,555]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="25.[155,233,1846,1865]" captionTargetBox="[211,1374,199,1810]" captionTargetId="figure-53@25.[210,1376,199,1814]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Figure 13. Australachalcus albipalpus (Parent) (male, unless mentioned otherwise). A, wing; B, female antenna; C, antenna; D, hypopygium; E, epandrial setae at base of epandrial lobe." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432023" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432023/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Figs 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="04FBBF9003220920FDADB247CA3FCA1B" box="[608,638,533,555]" captionStart="Figure 27" captionStartId="42.[142,220,1846,1865]" captionTargetBox="[231,1333,200,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-60@42.[229,1335,198,1814]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="Figure 27. Australachalcus variabilis sp. nov. (male). Hypopygial appendages. A, aedeagus; B, hypandrium, ventral view; C, epandrial lobe; D, ventral process of epandrium; E, epandrial lobe (top) and surstylus (bottom); F, cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432051/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">27</figureCitation>
). Hypandrium mostly with ventral apex clearly spined, or with raised marginal edge (
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FE6EB201CA6ECA58" box="[419,559,595,616]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FE6EB201CA6ECA58" box="[419,559,595,616]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group) (synapomorphy); aedeagus often with subapical modifications; epandrial lobe massive to slender with three epandrial setae at basis; midventral bristle of surstylus usually with apical flag (excl. 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FBF4B172CC93C905" baseAuthorityName="Van Duzee" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[1081,1234,288,309]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Enlinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsae">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FBF4B172CC93C905" box="[1081,1234,288,309]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. edwardsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FB28B172CDC4C906" box="[1253,1413,288,310]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incisicornis">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FB28B172CDC4C906" box="[1253,1413,288,310]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. incisicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (synapomorphy).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C7FA31503220920FCEBB13FCB81C9CD" blockId="6.[806,1422,365,509]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FCEBB13FCB21C9B2" box="[806,864,365,386]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Legs:</emphasis>
Femur I usually with erect basoventral bristle (exc. 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FCAEB1DECBAEC990" box="[867,1007,395,417]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FCAEB1DECBAEC990" box="[867,1007,395,417]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">A. variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Tibia I without (baso)dorsal bristle(s) (synapomorphy). Femur III with weak to moderately strong preapical bristle, inserted on lower 1/3 of anterior face.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C7FA31503220920FCEBB247CCE9CA59" blockId="6.[806,1422,533,617]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FCEBB247CBE5CA1A" box="[806,932,533,554]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Etymology:</emphasis>
Refers to the southern hemisphere (‘southern 
<taxonomicName id="5BC0D89603220920FC6AB266CC4CCA79" authorityName="LOEW" authorityYear="1857" box="[935,1037,564,585]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achalcus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AEB47F0703220920FC6AB266CC4CCA79" box="[935,1037,564,585]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Achalcus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’), where this genus reaches its highest levels of species richness.
</paragraph>
